Scope of the AIMFK Standard

The SSUM-AIM Formula Kernel (AIMFK) defines a deterministic methodology for performing symbolic mathematical computations through explicit transformation rules.

The kernel processes bounded symbolic tasks such as:

• formula evaluation
• symbolic substitution
• equation verification
• polynomial computation
• matrix operations
• symbolic simplification
• equation solving

Each task is executed through deterministic rule transformations.

Conceptually:

Result = Φ(Task, Rules, Inputs)

Where:

Task   = requested symbolic operation
Rules  = deterministic transformation rules
Inputs = task parameters

The computation produces:

• deterministic results
• transformation records (proof traces)
• replay-verifiable outputs


Deterministic Computation Discipline

The AIMFK methodology follows three deterministic rules.

Deterministic Execution
same task input → same result

Mutation Sensitivity
changed input → changed result

Replay Verification
re-execution of the same task produces the same output

These rules define deterministic formula intelligence.


What AIMFK Does NOT Do

The AIMFK standard does not:

• modify classical mathematics
• introduce probabilistic inference
• perform machine learning
• train statistical models
• simulate predictions
• inject randomness
• alter execution semantics

It performs deterministic symbolic computation only.


Conformance

An implementation conforms to the AIMFK Standard if it:

• executes symbolic transformations deterministically
• uses explicit rule-based transformations
• produces reproducible results for identical inputs
• preserves deterministic proof traces where applicable
• produces different outputs when task inputs differ

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• nondeterministic output ordering
• hidden state mutation
• adaptive runtime mutation

does not conform to the deterministic AIMFK standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.


